        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1962-06-27T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1962-06-27T00:00:00-05:00" n="310"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d310">
                <head>310. Memorandum From the President’s Military Aide (<persName
                        corresp="#p_CCV1" type="from">Clifton</persName>) to the President’s Special
                    Assistant for National Security Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_BMG2" type="to"
                        >Bundy</persName>)<note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d310fn0">Source:
                            <persName corresp="#p_KJF2">Kennedy</persName> Library, National
                        Security Files, Country Series, Saudi Arabia, 6/7/62–6/30/62. No
                        classification marking.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1962-06-27">June 27, 1962</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The President [<hi rend="italic">2 lines of source text not declassified</hi>]
                    asked that you get the following information: <list>
                        <label>a.</label>
                        <item>A resume of what we promised the King.<note n="1" xml:id="d310fn1"
                                >Reference is to King Saud.</note>
                        </item>
                        <label>b.</label>
                        <item>A résumé of what they promised us, especially in regard to the action
                            they were going to take on the Jewish question, and in regard to the
                            servicemen, etc.</item>
                        <label>c.</label>
                        <item>If, as they alleged, the radio transmitters we promised them were
                            unsatisfactory, why did we offer them? If they were satisfactory, what
                            is the difference of opinion that makes them take such a dim
                            view?</item>
                        <pb facs="0817" n="757" xml:id="pg_757"/>
                        <label>d.</label>
                        <item>Has the aid mission that we promised already departed? If not, why
                            not?</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>As a corollary to this, the President would like a few facts on the aid and
                    assistance we are giving the <gloss target="#t_UAR1">UAR</gloss>, compared to
                    what we are giving to that other friend. What is the financial situation,
                    especially in regard to oil, and what do they really need; what should we be
                    giving them?</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="strong">C.V. Clifton</hi>
                        </persName>
                        <note n="2" xml:id="d310fn2">Printed from a copy that bears this typed
                            signature.</note>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
